[2
Date: 29 Jun 2000 08:17:47 -0300
From: Carlos Brisola Marcondes <cbrisola@mbox1.ufsc.br>

[The epidemiology and epizootiology of leishmaniases are very complex and
there are many reservoirs and situations. The situation and form and
transmission, including reservoirs and vectors, must be studied in each
place. Certainly Dr. Zeledon, from Costa Rica, could inform us on the
situation in Nicaragua, so near and similar to his country.
It is impossible to generalize, blaming rodents as reservoirs and proposing
their control. For Central America, there are several publications on
leishmaniases in Belize, mostly by P. Williams, and from Panama, involving
Christensen, Herrer and others. For general methods of investigations and
reviews of epidemiology, Lainson's and Shaw's papers must be read.
References:
*WILLIAMS, P., 1970. Phlebotomine sandflies and leishmaniasis in British
Honduras (Belize). Trans. R. Soc. Trop. Med. Hyg., 64(3):317-368.
*DARCE, M.; J. MORAN;..., 1991. Etiology of human cutaneous leishmaniasis
in Nicaragua. Trans. R. Soc. Trop. Med. Hyg., 85(1):58-59.
*MISSONI, E. & R. MORELLI 1984 Survey of 259 cases of American cutaneous
leishmaniasis in Nicaragua. J. Trop. Med. Hyg., 87(4):159-165.
*DUARTE, Z.; J. MUNGUIA; M. OROZCO & J. C. GANTIER, 1994. First report of
visceral leishmaniasis in Nicaragua. Trans. R. Soc. Trop. Med. Hyg., 88(1):38.
*CHRISTENSEN, H. A.; G. B. FAIRCHILD; A. HERRER; C. M. JOHNSON; D. G. YOUNG
& A. M. DE VASQUEZ, 1983. The ecology of cutaneous leishmaniasis in the
Republic of Panama. J. Med. Entomol., 20(5):463-484.
*HERRER, A., H. A. CHRISTENSEN & R. J. BEUMER, 1973. Reservoir hosts of
cutaneous leishmaniasis among Panamanian forest mammals. Am. J. Trop. Med.
Hyg., 22( ):585-591.
*HERRER, A.; H. A. CHRISTENSEN & R. J. BEUMER, 1976. Epidemiological
patterns of cutaneous leishmaniasis in Panama. II. Incidental occurrence of
cases in no endemic settlements. Ann. Trop. Med. Parasitol., 70(1):67-71.
*ZELEDON, R.; H. HIDALGO; A. VIQUEZ & A. URBINA, 1989. Atypical cutaneous
leishmaniasis in a semiarid region of north-west Costa Rica. Trans. R. Soc.
Trop. Med. Hyg., 83(6):786.
*LAINSON, R.; J. J. SHAW; F. T. SILVEIRA; A. A. A. SOUZA; R. R. BRAGA & E.
A. Y. ISHIKAWA, 1994. The dermal leishmaniases of Brazil, with special
reference to the eco-epidemiology of the disease in Amazonia. Mem. Inst.
*LAINSON, R. & J. J. SHAW, 1992. A brief history of the genus _Leishmania_
(Protozoa: Kinetoplastida) in the Americas, with particular reference to
Amazonian Brazil. Ciencia Cultura, 44:94-106.
--
Prof. Dr. Carlos Brisola Marcondes
Depto Microb. Paras./CCB
UFSC-Campus Trindade
88040-900 Florianopolis (SC)
Brasil
<cbrisola@mbox1.ufsc.br>
[It appears that the outbreak takes place in an area known for endemic
cutaneous leishmaniasis. -Mod. EP
